        </div>

        <!-- T temper accordion -->
        <div class="t-temper-list">

          <div class="t-temper-item content-card-inner reveal">
            <button class="t-temper-header" aria-expanded="false">
              <div class="t-code">T1</div>
              <div class="t-header-text">
                <strong>Cooled from hot working + naturally aged</strong>
                <span class="t-desc-short">Products cooled from an elevated-temperature shaping process and naturally aged to a substantially stable condition.</span>
              </div>
              <svg class="t-chevron" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
            </button>
            <div class="t-temper-body">
              <p>The T1 temper applies to products that are not cold worked after cooling from hot working and for which mechanical properties have been stabilized by room-temperature aging. This temper applies to products shaped by extrusion, rolling, or other hot-working processes that are cooled sufficiently rapidly that they are in a partially supersaturated state.</p>
              <p><strong>Applicable alloys:</strong> 6005, 6060, 6063 (extrusions cooled from extrusion temperature)</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="t-temper-item content-card-inner reveal">
            <button class="t-temper-header" aria-expanded="false">
              <div class="t-code">T2</div>
              <div class="t-header-text">
                <strong>Cooled from hot working + cold worked + naturally aged</strong>
                <span class="t-desc-short">Products cooled from hot working, cold worked, and naturally aged to a substantially stable condition.</span>
              </div>
              <svg class="t-chevron" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
            </button>
            <div class="t-temper-body">
              <p>The T2 temper is similar to T1 except the product is cold worked (e.g., by flattening or straightening) after cooling from hot working to improve strength beyond that achieved in T1. The product is then naturally aged to a stable condition. This temper is relatively uncommon.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="t-temper-item content-card-inner reveal">
            <button class="t-temper-header" aria-expanded="false">
              <div class="t-code">T3</div>
              <div class="t-header-text">
                <strong>Solution heat treated + cold worked + naturally aged</strong>
                <span class="t-desc-short">Classic aerospace temper for 2xxx alloys. Example: 2024-T3</span>
              </div>
              <svg class="t-chevron" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
            </button>
            <div class="t-temper-body">
              <p>Products that are solution heat treated (dissolved alloying elements into solid solution at elevated temperature), quenched to retain the supersaturated state, then cold worked to improve strength, and finally naturally aged at room temperature to a substantially stable condition.</p>
              <p><strong>Common example:</strong> 2024-T3 is the standard aircraft fuselage skin alloy. Cold working after quenching typically consists of stretching 1&ndash;3% for plate products (designated T351) or cold rolling for sheet.</p>
              <p><strong>Sub-designations:</strong></p>
              <ul class="prop-list">
                <li><strong>T351</strong> &mdash; Stress relieved by stretching 1&ndash;3%, not further straightened</li>
                <li><strong>T3511</strong> &mdash; Stress relieved by stretching, minor straightening allowed</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="t-temper-item content-card-inner reveal">
            <button class="t-temper-header" aria-expanded="false">
              <div class="t-code">T4</div>
              <div class="t-header-text">
                <strong>Solution heat treated + naturally aged</strong>
                <span class="t-desc-short">Quenched and naturally aged without cold working. Example: 2024-T4, 6061-T4</span>
              </div>
              <svg class="t-chevron" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
            </button>
            <div class="t-temper-body">
              <p>Products solution heat treated and naturally aged to a substantially stable condition. Unlike T3, these products are not cold worked after quenching. Strength develops gradually over days to weeks at room temperature through natural precipitation hardening (formation of Guinier-Preston zones in the matrix).</p>
              <p><strong>Common examples:</strong> 2024-T4 (good formability, moderate strength), 6061-T4 (used where forming is required before aging to T6)</p>
              <p>Natural aging for 2024 reaches approximately 90% of stable strength within 4 days (96 hours) at room temperature. Full stabilization may take months.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="t-temper-item content-card-inner reveal">
            <button class="t-temper-header" aria-expanded="false">
              <div class="t-code">T5</div>
              <div class="t-header-text">
                <strong>Cooled from hot working + artificially aged</strong>
                <span class="t-desc-short">Air quenched from extrusion then aged. Example: 6063-T5</span>
              </div>
              <svg class="t-chevron" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
            </button>
            <div class="t-temper-body">
              <p>Products cooled from an elevated-temperature shaping process (typically extrusion) and then artificially aged. No separate solution heat treatment step is performed &mdash; the cooling from the hot working operation provides sufficient quench rate to retain adequate supersaturation for subsequent aging response.</p>
              <p><strong>Common example:</strong> 6063-T5 is the most widely used temper for architectural extrusions (window frames, curtain walls, decorative trim). The alloy is cooled from the extrusion press using fans (air quench) and then aged at approximately 175&ndash;205&deg;C for 1&ndash;8 hours.</p>
              <p><strong>6063-T5 vs 6063-T6:</strong> T5 achieves lower strength than T6 because air cooling from the press is less effective than a separate water quench. For 6063, T5 provides approximately 150 MPa yield vs 215 MPa yield for T6.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="t-temper-item content-card-inner reveal">
            <button class="t-temper-header" aria-expanded="false">
              <div class="t-code">T6</div>
              <div class="t-header-text">
                <strong>Solution heat treated + artificially aged</strong>
                <span class="t-desc-short">Peak-aged for maximum strength. Examples: 6061-T6, 7075-T6</span>
              </div>
              <svg class="t-chevron" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
            </button>
            <div class="t-temper-body">
              <p>Products solution heat treated and then artificially aged. T6 represents the <strong>peak-aged condition</strong> &mdash; aged to achieve maximum hardness and strength. This is the most common high-strength temper for heat-treatable alloys and the standard temper for structural applications.</p>
              <p>The process involves three critical steps: (1) soak at solution treatment temperature to dissolve precipitates, (2) rapid quench (usually water) to retain supersaturated solid solution, (3) controlled aging at elevated temperature to precipitate fine, uniformly distributed strengthening particles.</p>
              <p><strong>Common examples:</strong></p>
              <ul class="prop-list">
                <li><strong>6061-T6</strong> &mdash; The most widely used structural aluminum alloy. UTS 310 MPa, yield 275 MPa</li>
                <li><strong>7075-T6</strong> &mdash; Highest strength common alloy. UTS 570 MPa, yield 505 MPa</li>
                <li><strong>6063-T6</strong> &mdash; Architectural extrusions requiring higher strength</li>
              </ul>
              <p><strong>Sub-designations:</strong></p>
              <ul class="prop-list">
                <li><strong>T61</strong> &mdash; Under-aged (slightly below peak), better formability</li>
                <li><strong>T651</strong> &mdash; T6 + stress relieved by stretching 1&ndash;3% (plate products)</li>
                <li><strong>T6511</strong> &mdash; T6 + stress relieved by stretching, minor straightening allowed (extrusions)</li>
                <li><strong>T652</strong> &mdash; T6 + stress relieved by compression</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="t-temper-item content-card-inner reveal">
            <button class="t-temper-header" aria-expanded="false">
              <div class="t-code">T7</div>
              <div class="t-header-text">
                <strong>Solution heat treated + overaged / stabilized</strong>
                <span class="t-desc-short">Aged beyond peak strength for improved corrosion resistance. Example: 7075-T73</span>
              </div>
              <svg class="t-chevron" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
            </button>
            <div class="t-temper-body">
              <p>Products solution heat treated and artificially overaged (aged beyond the peak-strength condition). Overaging deliberately sacrifices some strength to achieve specific properties: improved resistance to stress corrosion cracking (SCC), better exfoliation corrosion resistance, or improved dimensional stability.</p>
              <p><strong>Common examples:</strong></p>
              <ul class="prop-list">
                <li><strong>7075-T73</strong> &mdash; Overaged for SCC resistance. Strength reduced ~15% vs T6 but much better corrosion resistance. Used in thick structural forgings and components exposed to sustained tensile stress</li>
                <li><strong>7075-T76</strong> &mdash; Overaged specifically for exfoliation corrosion resistance</li>
                <li><strong>7050-T7451</strong> &mdash; Overaged + stress relieved by stretching. Common aerospace plate</li>
                <li><strong>7075-T7351</strong> &mdash; Overaged + stress relieved plate for machined components</li>
              </ul>
              <p>Two-step aging (e.g., 120&deg;C for 6hr + 165&deg;C for 24hr) is often used to achieve the optimum balance between strength and corrosion resistance in T7-type tempers for 7xxx alloys.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="t-temper-item content-card-inner reveal">
            <button class="t-temper-header" aria-expanded="false">
              <div class="t-code">T8</div>
              <div class="t-header-text">
                <strong>Solution heat treated + cold worked + artificially aged</strong>
                <span class="t-desc-short">Cold worked before aging for enhanced strength. Example: 2024-T81</span>
              </div>
              <svg class="t-chevron" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
            </button>
            <div class="t-temper-body">
              <p>Products solution heat treated, cold worked to improve strength (and provide nucleation sites for precipitates), then artificially aged. Cold working before aging accelerates precipitation and refines precipitate distribution, yielding higher strength and better properties than T6 alone.</p>
              <p><strong>Common examples:</strong></p>
              <ul class="prop-list">
                <li><strong>2024-T81</strong> &mdash; Solution treated, cold worked, then aged at 190&deg;C. Higher strength and better SCC resistance than T3</li>
                <li><strong>2024-T851</strong> &mdash; T8 + stress relieved by stretching</li>
                <li><strong>2024-T86</strong> &mdash; Solution treated + 6% cold work + artificial aging. Used in cryogenic applications</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="t-temper-item content-card-inner reveal">
            <button class="t-temper-header" aria-expanded="false">
              <div class="t-code">T9</div>
              <div class="t-header-text">
                <strong>Solution heat treated + artificially aged + cold worked</strong>
                <span class="t-desc-short">Cold worked after aging for additional strength.</span>
              </div>
              <svg class="t-chevron" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
            </button>
            <div class="t-temper-body">
              <p>Products solution heat treated, artificially aged, then cold worked to further increase strength. The cold working after aging adds dislocation strengthening on top of precipitation hardening. T9 is relatively uncommon and used for specialized applications requiring the highest possible strength from a given alloy.</p>
              <p><strong>Example:</strong> 2024-T9 and some 6xxx alloy fastener wire/rod products.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="t-temper-item content-card-inner reveal">
            <button class="t-temper-header" aria-expanded="false">
              <div class="t-code">T10</div>
              <div class="t-header-text">
                <strong>Cooled from hot working + cold worked + artificially aged</strong>
                <span class="t-desc-short">Similar to T5 but with added cold working before aging.</span>
              </div>
              <svg class="t-chevron" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
            </button>
            <div class="t-temper-body">
              <p>Products cooled from an elevated-temperature shaping process, cold worked to improve strength, then artificially aged. This temper is similar to T5 but includes a cold working step between cooling and aging. It is used for products where the additional cold working before aging provides meaningful property improvement.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Section 6: Process Temperature & Time Reference -->
      <div class="section-block reveal">
        <h2 class="section-heading"><span class="section-num">06</span> Process Temperature &amp; Time Reference</h2>
        <p class="section-intro">The following table provides typical heat treatment parameters for commonly used aluminum alloys. These values are representative; actual parameters may vary based on product form, thickness, and specific alloy composition.</p>

